																		How to Cross-Reference
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/wrongjohnsilver" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2000367); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2000367&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610251598" alt="WrongJohnSilver" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2000367)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/wrongjohnsilver" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2000367); return false;" >WrongJohnSilver</a></span> <span class="odate time_1462797018 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">09 May 2016 12:30</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2505739">
									

<p>We hear a lot of conflicting advice regarding cross-references: it's okay, it's not okay, etc. Hopefully we can take a moment to clear it up for new (and veteran) authors.</p>
<p>In my opinion, cross-references are fine. However, you can't just throw anyone into the mix with your idea and make it work. You've got to know why you're using it. Here are my observations on how to make a cross-ref succeed:</p>
<ul>
<li>The referenced SCP needs a purpose that isn't better solved by another SCP. So, if you randomly just add an SCP you like to your SCP's documentation, it's going to look fake and be downvoted. However, I used <a href="/scp-173">SCP-173</a> in my write-up of <a href="/scp-2289">SCP-2289</a>. Normally, yes, invoking 173 is not a good idea if you're a new author, but in this case, it's about a D-class janitor with a bunch of extra eyes; it's precisely the sort of thing that might end up important when cleaning 173, and not any other object in containment.</li>
<li>March Madness aside, it's not a race or arena. Saying stuff like &quot;SCP-A can totally pwn SCP-B&quot; is not going to earn you any favors (whether you're writing A or B).</li>
<li>Your SCP should stand on its own without reference to other SCPs. Cross-references add interconnectivity and world cohesion, but they should not be the raison d'etre of yours. An idea that wouldn't work, for example: Let's say you really like <a href="/scp-049">SCP-049</a> and want to give him a magic scalpel. If you make the magic scalpel as an SCP and give it to 049 and say it's his, the article will fall flat, hard. Why let any SCP have it, and not contain it? If an SCP is going to have it, why 049 and not, say, <a href="/scp-542">SCP-542</a>? It just looks&#8230; fanboyish. Now, you could write a tale in which 049 has a magic scalpel, but if it's an object that exists on its own, it has to have very real narrative purpose on its own.</li>
</ul>
<p>Any other thoughts about what makes a good or bad cross-reference?</p>

