															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/mrwrong" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2039383); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2039383&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610251598" alt="MrWrong" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2039383)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/mrwrong" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2039383); return false;" >MrWrong</a></span> <span class="odate time_1462799229 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">09 May 2016 13:07</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2505750">
									

<p>When I look at cross-references, I would look at how they add on to the articles involved. Using SCP-2833 as an example, it cross-references SCP-2406 and SCP-029.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>2406 and 2833 are both part of the CotBG-Sarkic conflict, so there is a pre-existing thematic link between the two. 2833's reference on 2406 is that they are &quot;a race of giants&quot; and that they &quot;threatened and exiled&quot; Karcist Vaski. It paints how a Sarkicist perceives the Colossi's arrival on Adytum, threatening the Sarkcist's way of life. And it was that battle that Vaski fled from, leaving those he knows in Adytum at the mercy of the Colossi.</p>
<p>As for 029, I incorporated it after I place the Thuggee as opposers of 2833 since 029 is associated with the Thuggee. As I cast 2833 as the &quot;villains&quot;, the Thuggee are inevitably the &quot;hero&quot; and that feels contradictory to 029's m.o. And then, I recalled the bad reputation and mass persecution of the Thuggee by British colonials (which is rare since the British usually leave the Indians be in terms of socio-cultural affairs). The result was to have 029 be a(n unwilling) corrupter planted among the Thuggee as a false goddess to latch onto.</p>
<p>In the end, I feel that it adds a layer of meaning onto 029 that is not <em>just</em> another monster that kills people and is forced into the role. The fact that the Sarkicists that made her are willing to abandon her also plays in on the Neo-Sarkicists' willingness to sacrifice others for their own goals. It also shows 2833 as not an invincible force as they need to be rescued by another group of Sarkicists to save themselves from extinction.</p>
<p>Another cross-reference I retroactively added is a reference to Sigma-3 in <a href="/the-reassembled-one">The Reassembled One</a>. In that article, I went on about the characters complaining about hidden Jailors who are Library contributors and use the cross-reference to imply that there are more such of these accusations levied on Library contributors (and that Sigma-3's in-universe author and my article's L.S. are not isolated cases who accuse others of treason to the Library).</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>So overall, I feel that cross-references should have meaning to your article and the cross-referenced material.</p>

							</div>

								
